			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I know someone else touched on this briefly, but I myself would like to expound upon the virtues of &quot;track.&quot;  I can't do this enough, it is as much our raison d'etre as Spirit of Wolf is the Shaman's.  I didn't start looking at it until I was 3rd level or so, and I was astonished at how useful it was.<BR>
<BR>
Track is a highly useful skill for the &quot;fetch&quot; style of partying.  This would be when the party groups at some landmark, and one member goes out, pricks a monster (a bow is good for this) and then beats feet back to the party.  Track is useful for both finding the monster in the firt place, and as an added bonus, if you've lost sight of your part, track can lead you back to them quickly when there's a beast munching on your heels.  Generally, I tell the party what my &quot;track&quot; scanner shows, and we decide what I should fetch.  Don't range too far now, but it does allow you to be more selective than everyone else.<BR>
<BR>
Also, Shamans are occassionally called upon for their SoW, so can Rangers make use of their skills for profit and exp.  I was once in Everfrost, hunting snow orcs and your occasional polar bear, and I managed to catch wind of one Karg (last name forgotten by the player.)  Well, I tracked him down to his source, and shouted that I had found him.  You will not believe the offers I received for this poor man's location, both to buy a polar bear cloak from him (see the Everfrost quests) or to kill him for a two-handed sword he apparently has.  I've also been called upon to hunt Will-o-wisps, Momma Mammoths, and other critters that I couldn't take alone.  The moral: find out what's valuable, and if there's a resonable market out there, market that information, even if its something you can't take yourself.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, it can make those hard-to-find rare spawning monsters that give quest items all the easier to locate.  You don't have to rely on shouting for finding someone quest-oriented, you can just wander until you catch their trail, then home in.  So just remember, Track is your friend.  Track is your specialty.  Find new and innovative ways to use it.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
